event: response.output_text.delta
data: {"type":"response.output_text.delta","content_index":0,"delta":".","item_id":"msg_033a97a9e38891b10169e3dc50bd188194b0f69a6a0a581987","logprobs":[],"obfuscation":"TGbFiFBLKcw56UN","output_index":1,"sequence_number":2140}

event: response.output_text.done
data: {"type":"response.output_text.done","content_index":0,"item_id":"msg_033a97a9e38891b10169e3dc50bd188194b0f69a6a0a581987","logprobs":[],"output_index":1,"sequence_number":2141,"text":"## Crowd-avoid + low-budget rules (do this first)\n1. **Start early (aim 7:30–8:30)** at each “famous” spot.\n2. **Avoid lunch-time walking in hotspots** (10:30–15:30 is peak crowd time).\n3. **Group activities by area** so you don’t waste money/energy on transit.\n4. **Pick 1 “paid” thing per day max** (temple/garden/sake museum).\n5. **Use IC card + walking** instead of taxis. If you’ll ride lots of buses in one day, check whether a day pass is actually cheaper for your route.\n\n---\n\n# Day 1 — West Kyoto (Arashiyama + Saga): nature + temples (low-crowd strategy)\n**Step 1: Go to Arashiyama first thing**\n- Morning: take JR/S-bahn to **Saga-Arashiyama** (or Arashiyama area) and arrive **before 8:00**.\n- **Bamboo grove walk**: go early, then **leave the main grove quickly** to reduce crowd time.\n\n**Step 2: Do temples next (Arashiyama is still calmer before 10:00)**\n- **Tenryu-ji** (classic garden/temple).  \n  - Paid, but it’s a good “culture per yen” stop.\n- Keep the pace brisk—don’t linger in the most photographed lanes.\n\n**Step 3: Switch to a quieter, more local-feeling temple**\n- **Otagi Nenbutsu-ji** (hundreds of small stone statues).\n  - Usually far less crowded than the bamboo area.\n\n**Step 4: Add the scenic tram instead of another bus**\n- Ride a short section of the **Randen (tram) line** for a budget-friendly “Kyoto local” feel.\n- If you’re tired: skip long rides and just enjoy the tram + nearby streets.\n\n**Step 5: Evening decompress (less central, less crowded)**\n- Walk along the **Katsura River** area or a quieter stretch near Arashiyama after 17:00.\n- Dinner (budget): ramen/udon near tram/JR stations.\n\n---\n\n# Day 2 — Southern Kyoto (Fushimi Inari + sake district + Toji): religion + local industry\n**Step 1: Fushimi Inari Taisha before crowds**\n- Arrive **around 7:00–7:30**.\n- Don’t just stay on the main trail—**take a side route / loop** to see more and feel less congested.\n\n**Step 2: Sake district culture (choose 1 place, not many)**\n- After descending, go to **Fushimi sake streets/museums**.\n- Pick **one**:\n  - A **sake museum** with tastings (often ~1,000 yen-ish), or\n  - A **small brewery tour** (timing-dependent; check the day’s tour hours).\n- This is a very “Kyoto culture” experience that doesn’t require expensive tours across multiple neighborhoods.\n\n**Step 3: Toji (UNESCO temple area) for a calm, cultured contrast**\n- Head to **Toji Temple** area for architecture + atmosphere.\n- Lunch nearby (budget-friendly options are common around major stations/temple areas).\n\n**Step 4: Optional cultural “local life”**\n- Try a **public bath (sentō)** in the evening (often ~400–900 yen).\n  - It’s authentically local and usually not crowded compared with tourist attractions.\n  - (Bring small cash, follow basic bath etiquette.)\n\n**Step 5: Quiet evening walk**\n- Walk along **Kamogawa River** away from the densest Gion lanes (or go toward where you’re staying instead of “chasing lights”).\n\n---\n\n# Day 3 — North Kyoto outskirts (Shimogamo + Kurama/Kibune): shrines + countryside vibe\n**Step 1: Start with Shimogamo Shrine**\n- Go to **Shimogamo Jinja** early (**~8:00–9:00**).  \n- Walk slowly through the grounds and surrounding area—this one stays calmer than the “top 3” tourist temples.\n\n**Step 2: Head to Kurama (less crowded)**\n- Travel to **Kurama** (about 40–70 minutes depending on route).\n- Visit **Kurama-dera** (temple in a forested area; very atmospheric).\n\n**Step 3: Walk/roam to Kibune**\n- Take the valley/rural route toward **Kibune**.\n- This is one of the best “avoid crowds” moves because it’s more of a nature/countryside plan than a landmark checklist.\n\n**Step 4: Kibune Shrine + local meal**\n- Visit **Kibune Jinja**.\n- For budget culture, aim for a set lunch. A famous local specialty here is **yudōfu (tofu hot pot)** (price varies, but it’s a Kyoto-specific experience).\n\n**Step 5: Optional onsen**\n- If you want a low-cost “Kyoto local” finale, consider **Kurama/Kibune-area onsen** (varies by facility; generally not as pricey as tourist experiences).\n\n---\n\n## Simple budget snapshot (very rough)\n- **Transit (3 days):** ~2,000–4,000 yen depending on how much bus/subway you use\n- **Paid entries:** ~1,500–3,500 yen total if you choose **only 1 paid attraction/day**\n- **Food:** keep breakfast inexpensive (conbini/cheap noodle/udon) and lunches simple → often ~4,000–7,000 yen total per person for 3 days (excluding higher-end dinners)\n\nIf you tell me your **hotel area** (or nearest station) and whether you’re visiting on a **weekday vs weekend**, I can tighten the routes/timing to reduce crowds even more."}

event: response.content_part.done
data: {"type":"response.content_part.done","content_index":0,"item_id":"msg_033a97a9e38891b10169e3dc50bd188194b0f69a6a0a581987","output_index":1,"part":{"type":"output_text","annotations":[],"logprobs":[],"text":"## Crowd-avoid + low-budget rules (do this first)\n1. **Start early (aim 7:30–8:30)** at each “famous” spot.\n2. **Avoid lunch-time walking in hotspots** (10:30–15:30 is peak crowd time).\n3. **Group activities by area** so you don’t waste money/energy on transit.\n4. **Pick 1 “paid” thing per day max** (temple/garden/sake museum).\n5. **Use IC card + walking** instead of taxis. If you’ll ride lots of buses in one day, check whether a day pass is actually cheaper for your route.\n\n---\n\n# Day 1 — West Kyoto (Arashiyama + Saga): nature + temples (low-crowd strategy)\n**Step 1: Go to Arashiyama first thing**\n- Morning: take JR/S-bahn to **Saga-Arashiyama** (or Arashiyama area) and arrive **before 8:00**.\n- **Bamboo grove walk**: go early, then **leave the main grove quickly** to reduce crowd time.\n\n**Step 2: Do temples next (Arashiyama is still calmer before 10:00)**\n- **Tenryu-ji** (classic garden/temple).  \n  - Paid, but it’s a good “culture per yen” stop.\n- Keep the pace brisk—don’t linger in the most photographed lanes.\n\n**Step 3: Switch to a quieter, more local-feeling temple**\n- **Otagi Nenbutsu-ji** (hundreds of small stone statues).\n  - Usually far less crowded than the bamboo area.\n\n**Step 4: Add the scenic tram instead of another bus**\n- Ride a short section of the **Randen (tram) line** for a budget-friendly “Kyoto local” feel.\n- If you’re tired: skip long rides and just enjoy the tram + nearby streets.\n\n**Step 5: Evening decompress (less central, less crowded)**\n- Walk along the **Katsura River** area or a quieter stretch near Arashiyama after 17:00.\n- Dinner (budget): ramen/udon near tram/JR stations.\n\n---\n\n# Day 2 — Southern Kyoto (Fushimi Inari + sake district + Toji): religion + local industry\n**Step 1: Fushimi Inari Taisha before crowds**\n- Arrive **around 7:00–7:30**.\n- Don’t just stay on the main trail—**take a side route / loop** to see more and feel less congested.\n\n**Step 2: Sake district culture (choose 1 place, not many)**\n- After descending, go to **Fushimi sake streets/museums**.\n- Pick **one**:\n  - A **sake museum** with tastings (often ~1,000 yen-ish), or\n  - A **small brewery tour** (timing-dependent; check the day’s tour hours).\n- This is a very “Kyoto culture” experience that doesn’t require expensive tours across multiple neighborhoods.\n\n**Step 3: Toji (UNESCO temple area) for a calm, cultured contrast**\n- Head to **Toji Temple** area for architecture + atmosphere.\n- Lunch nearby (budget-friendly options are common around major stations/temple areas).\n\n**Step 4: Optional cultural “local life”**\n- Try a **public bath (sentō)** in the evening (often ~400–900 yen).\n  - It’s authentically local and usually not crowded compared with tourist attractions.\n  - (Bring small cash, follow basic bath etiquette.)\n\n**Step 5: Quiet evening walk**\n- Walk along **Kamogawa River** away from the densest Gion lanes (or go toward where you’re staying instead of “chasing lights”).\n\n---\n\n# Day 3 — North Kyoto outskirts (Shimogamo + Kurama/Kibune): shrines + countryside vibe\n**Step 1: Start with Shimogamo Shrine**\n- Go to **Shimogamo Jinja** early (**~8:00–9:00**).  \n- Walk slowly through the grounds and surrounding area—this one stays calmer than the “top 3” tourist temples.\n\n**Step 2: Head to Kurama (less crowded)**\n- Travel to **Kurama** (about 40–70 minutes depending on route).\n- Visit **Kurama-dera** (temple in a forested area; very atmospheric).\n\n**Step 3: Walk/roam to Kibune**\n- Take the valley/rural route toward **Kibune**.\n- This is one of the best “avoid crowds” moves because it’s more of a nature/countryside plan than a landmark checklist.\n\n**Step 4: Kibune Shrine + local meal**\n- Visit **Kibune Jinja**.\n- For budget culture, aim for a set lunch. A famous local specialty here is **yudōfu (tofu hot pot)** (price varies, but it’s a Kyoto-specific experience).\n\n**Step 5: Optional onsen**\n- If you want a low-cost “Kyoto local” finale, consider **Kurama/Kibune-area onsen** (varies by facility; generally not as pricey as tourist experiences).\n\n---\n\n## Simple budget snapshot (very rough)\n- **Transit (3 days):** ~2,000–4,000 yen depending on how much bus/subway you use\n- **Paid entries:** ~1,500–3,500 yen total if you choose **only 1 paid attraction/day**\n- **Food:** keep breakfast inexpensive (conbini/cheap noodle/udon) and lunches simple → often ~4,000–7,000 yen total per person for 3 days (excluding higher-end dinners)\n\nIf you tell me your **hotel area** (or nearest station) and whether you’re visiting on a **weekday vs weekend**, I can tighten the routes/timing to reduce crowds even more."},"sequence_number":2142}

